#Convert the "VClass" column from a plain object type into an ordered categorical type
sedan_group = ['Midsize Cars', 'Compact Cars', 'Subcompact Cars', 'Large Cars', 'Minicompact Cars']
vclass = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=sedan_group)
df_clean['VClass'] = df_clean['VClass'].astype(vclass);

Assessment¶

There are no missing values in the dataset table.

There are no duplicate rows in the dataset.

The datatypes for all entries are in the correct format.

Formats of data in the columns is correct.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset is in Comma-separated values(csv) format with a total of 20 columns and 3929 row entries. Most variables are numeric in nature with make, model, VClass, drive, trans and fuelType being strings.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features are VClass,Engine size, year and combined fuel efficiency.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The most prominent feature that will contribute to the investigation is fuel efficiency and we will take a look at how various variables contribute and relate to fuel efficiency. We will compare fuel efficiency with variables such as engine size, year and Vehicle Class.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Vehicle Class( VClass) is skewed to the right which means that more values are concentrated to the left side of the distribution. Variables drive and trans have a bi-modial distribution. Trans_type variable has a bi-modal distribution as it only has two variables namely Automatic and Manual count. The fuel efficiency(comb) variable has a sphericity distribution.

Transformation performed involved converting the "VClass" column from a object data type into an ordered categorical type which are much easier to visualize.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

There were various variables with outliers in their visualizations such as transmission type(trans), fuel_type, drive, make and combustion(comb) variables. The data set was analyzed for null values using the .isnull() function and duplicates using the .duplicated() function and was found to be tidy and ready for analysis.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Combined fuel efficiency has a high correlation with co2 emission. As more fuel is burnt, more co2 emission occurs. Fuel efficiency and fuel displacement are highly corrlated. As fuel is diplaced, it is combusted in the same proportion.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Combined fuel efficiency and co2 emissions have a a highly negative correlation. This is also the same for variables fuel displacement(displ) and fuel efficiency.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Investigation of fuel efficiency against fuel combustion in this section was further looked into by looking at the impact of the three features. The multivariate exploration showed that there is a relationship between the amount of fuel displaced , combined fuel efficiency and co2 emissions.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The three features are closely dependent on each other as the occurence of one variable results to the occurrence of either the other variables.

Conclusions¶

The analysis found a high correlation between the variables being investigated which mainly were displ, comb and co2. Steps taken in the data exploration involved importing the relevant libraries relating to exploring the data visually, uploading the dataset into jupyter notebook, checking whether the data is tidy before conducting exploration. Exploration was done in three phases namely, Univariate which involved looking at one variable, Multivariate, which involved looking at two variables and finally Multivariate which involved looking at three variables and how they relate to each other.
